<div class="container">
  <div class="header">
    <h1>📡 Network Forensics & Vulnerability Assessment</h1>
    <p>Wireshark analysis · Nmap interpretation · OS fingerprinting · Nessus Ghostcat findings</p>
    <p style="margin-top: 0.75rem; font-size: 0.85rem;">Based on academic report – flags & technical walkthrough</p>
  </div>

  <!-- Question 1 -->
  <div class="section">
    <div class="section-title">🔎 1. Packet analysis (Wireshark) <span class="badge">base64 decode</span></div>
    <p>After observing anomalous packets in the capture, a suspicious Base64 string was extracted and decoded.</p>
    <div class="img-placeholder">
      🧩 [Wireshark screenshot] Unique packet anomaly → copied Base64 payload → decoded via base64decode.org
    </div>
    <div class="flag">🏁 Flag: <strong>SUCTF2023[ai_is_cool]</strong></div>
    <p><em>Methodology:</em> Identified outlier frame → copied raw data → Base64 decoding revealed plaintext flag.</p>
  </div>

  <!-- Question 2 -->
  <div class="section">
    <div class="section-title">📦 2. Packet2.pcap – FTP stream & Tic‑Tac‑Toe cipher</div>
    <p>FTP commands and responses were scrambled. Extracted the TCP stream and reconstructed the message.</p>
    <pre>Apply filter: tcp.stream eq 2 → retrieved encoded data</pre>
    <div class="img-placeholder">
      🧩 [Google doc / dcode.fr snapshot] Tic‑Tac‑Toe cipher decoding interface
    </div>
    <p><strong>Decoded plaintext:</strong> <code>EX MACHINA AVA</code></p>
    <div class="flag">🏁 Flag: <strong>SUCTF2023{EX MACHINA AVA}</strong></div>
    <p><em>Process:</em> Reassembled TCP stream → recognised pattern as Tic‑Tac‑Toe cipher → online decoder produced final flag.</p>
  </div>

  <!-- Question 3: Nmap output -->
  <div class="section">
    <div class="section-title">🖧 3. Nmap scan interpretation</div>
    <p><strong>Target services & versions:</strong></p>
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr><th>Port</th><th>Service</th><th>Version</th><th>Potential attacker actions</th></tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td>21/tcp</td><td>FTP</td><td>vsftpd 2.3.4</td><td>Anonymous login, upload/download, backdoor (port 6200) → root shell</td></tr>
        <tr><td>22/tcp</td><td>SSH</td><td>OpenSSH 5.3p1</td><td>Brute‑force credentials, user enumeration, weak ciphers</td></tr>
        <tr><td>80/tcp</td><td>HTTP</td><td>Apache 2.2.8</td><td>Range header DoS, request smuggling, possible RCE via mod_cgi/PHP</td></tr>
        <tr><td>139,445/tcp</td><td>SMB</td><td>Windows 7 SP1</td><td><strong>EternalBlue (MS17‑010)</strong> unauthenticated RCE, wormable attacks</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <h3 style="margin: 1rem 0 0.5rem 0;">🔐 Vulnerabilities per version</h3>
    <ul style="margin-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li><strong>vsftpd 2.3.4</strong> – Backdoor command execution (CVE-2011-2523).</li>
      <li><strong>OpenSSH 5.3p1</strong> – User enumeration (CVE-2018-15473), weak algorithms.</li>
      <li><strong>Apache 2.2.8</strong> – Range header DoS (CVE-2007-6750), HTTP request smuggling.</li>
      <li><strong>Windows 7 SP1 (SMB)</strong> – EternalBlue (CVE-2017-0144), SMBv1 multiple flaws.</li>
    </ul>

    <div class="risk-high">
      <strong>⚠️ Highest risk: Port 445 (SMB) on Windows 7 SP1</strong><br>
      Microsoft ended mainstream support; no patches without ESU. EternalBlue allows unauthenticated remote code execution, used by WannaCry/NotPetya.
    </div>

    <h3>🎯 Attack path</h3>
    <ol style="margin-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li>Reconnaissance: Nmap <code>smb-vuln-ms17-010</code> script</li>
      <li>Initial compromise: Metasploit exploit/windows/smb/ms17_010_eternalblue</li>
      <li>Post‑exploitation: Dump hashes (mimikatz), enable RDP, pivot to internal networks</li>
    </ol>

    <h3>🛡️ Remediation</h3>
    <ul>
      <li>vsftpd → upgrade to patched version / disable anonymous upload</li>
      <li>SSH → upgrade OpenSSH, disable weak ciphers, enforce key‑based auth + fail2ban</li>
      <li>Apache → upgrade to latest (2.4.x), disable unnecessary modules</li>
      <li>Windows 7 → migrate to supported OS, apply MS17-010 patch, disable SMBv1</li>
      <li>General: Regular vulnerability scanning + patch management + least privilege</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <!-- Question 4: OS Fingerprinting TTL -->
  <div class="section">
    <div class="section-title">📡 4. OS fingerprinting – TTL analysis</div>
    <div class="card-grid">
      <div class="card">
        <strong>🖥️ Image 1 (ICMP ping)</strong>
        <pre>64 bytes from localhost (::1): ttl=64 time=0.063 ms</pre>
        <p>Default TTL 64 → <strong>Linux / macOS / Unix-like</strong><br>Answer: <code>Linux</code></p>
      </div>
      <div class="card">
        <strong>🌐 Image 2 (Cisco router)</strong>
        <div class="img-placeholder" style="margin:0; padding:0.5rem;">[Cisco IOS TTL pattern: usually 255]</div>
        <p><strong>Answer: Cisco router</strong> (TTL 255 common, specific OS fingerprint)</p>
      </div>
      <div class="card">
        <strong>🪟 Image 3 (Windows)</strong>
        <div class="img-placeholder" style="margin:0; padding:0.5rem;">[Windows default TTL 128 / 32]</div>
        <p><strong>Answer: Windows</strong> (TTL initial 128 for Windows 10/11, 32 for older)</p>
      </div>
    </div>
    <p><em>Methodology:</em> Analysed TTL values from captured ICMP replies – each OS family uses a characteristic starting TTL.</p>
  </div>

  <!-- Question 5: Nessus Ghostcat -->
  <div class="section">
    <div class="section-title">👻 5. Nessus scan – Ghostcat vulnerability (AJP)</div>
    <p>Analysis of <code>Network_Scan.nessus</code> focused on critical findings named "Ghostcat".</p>
    <table>
      <tr><th style="width: 35%;">Affected port</th><td><strong>9009</strong> (also commonly 8009 – AJP protocol)</td></tr>
      <tr><th>Affected protocol</th><td>AJP (Apache JServ Protocol) version ajp13 – binary communication between Tomcat and web server</td></tr>
      <tr><th>CVSS score</th><td><strong>9.8 (Critical)</strong> – CVSS:3.1/AV:N/AC:L/PR:N/UI:N/S:U/C:H/I:H/A:H</td></tr>
      <tr><th>Exploit details (CVSS metrics)</th><td>
        • AV:N (Attack Vector: Network) – remotely exploitable<br>
        • AC:L (Low Attack Complexity) – reliable exploitation<br>
        • PR:N (No privileges required) – unauthenticated access<br>
        • Impact: full confidentiality, integrity, availability compromise
      </td></tr>
      <tr><th>CVE number</th><td><strong>CVE-2020-1938</strong> (Ghostcat / AJP file read/inclusion)</td></tr>
    </table>
    <p><strong>Impact:</strong> Allows unauthenticated remote read/inclusion of web application files, potentially leading to RCE if session deserialization is abused.</p>
    <div class="flag">🔧 Remediation: Disable AJP if not required, upgrade Tomcat to 9.0.31+, 8.5.51+, or set <code>secretRequired</code> attribute with strong authentication.</div>
  </div>

